\begin_layout Standard
This paper exploits and exogenous increase in the availability of local
 content in the Setswana language in South African, in order to isolate
 the effect on internet usage among native speakers.
 In 2010 Google collaborated with a Botswanan team of linguists 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "otlogetswe2010setswana"

\end_inset

 to make its Botswanan website (
\begin_inset Flex Code
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
google.co.bw
\end_layout

\end_inset

) available in the local language: `Setswana'.
 In addition to being spoken in Botswana, there is also a sizable population
 of Setswana directly across the border in South Africa, where it is also
 one of the official state languages.
 This therefore also led to the introduction of the Setswana language on
 the South African Google website (
\begin_inset Flex Code
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
google.co.za
\end_layout

\end_inset

), as spillover of the translation work performed for Google's Botswanan
 website.
 This change led to a large increase in the number of native Setswana speakers
 reporting to have spent some amount of money in the past 30 days on internet
 access.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Google Search interface represent a very small number of words on the
 internet and it is not required to use a certain interface language in
 order to search for content in this language.
 However, the search page is in many cases the first website viewed by users.
 Asides from being able to understand the interface of the website, having
 this interface be in a local language also encourages usage of this local
 language, which in turn reveals more local language content.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In short, we can identify several major channels which promote increase
 online engagement, which together constitute the theory of change.
 Firstly, the ability to read and understand the words of the interface
 increases the chance that user continues using the website and the internet
 at large.
 Secondly, the visibility of local language content increases the likelihood
 of the user entering search queries in the local language and thereby finding
 more content in the local language.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The vast majority of internet access is developing countries is through
 handheld devices such as smartphones.
 However, due to the limited `real estate' (surface area of the screen)
 on a mobile website, the link to changing the interface language is replace
 with a dropdown menu that reveals the additional language options.
 Generally, the website will default the the operating system (Android /
 iOS) language, however, since many local African languages are not available
 as a system language, this is not possible there.
 The fact that the introduction seems to benefit desktop usage but not mobile
 usage is further substantiated by our results that isolate an increase
 in computer ownership, but no increase in cell phone ownership.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In addition to the increase in the number of individuals spending on an
 internet connection, we also find a positive effect on the number of individual
s living in households with a computer.
\end_layout

