\begin_layout Subsection
Identification Strategy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:identification"

\end_inset

This paper exploits the introduction of the Setswana interface language
 to Google Search in South Africa as a spillover of the development of that
 interface for the Botswanan Google Search website.
 By comparing the number of native Setswana speakers in South Africa being
 internet users, with the number of South Africans with a different native
 language around the same time, we isolate the effect of this introduction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Setswana language was first developed for the Botswanan Google Search
 website (
\begin_inset Flex Code
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
google.co.bw
\end_layout

\end_inset

).
 As such, the introduction of Setswana to the South African Google Search
 (
\begin_inset Flex Code
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
google.co.za
\end_layout

\end_inset

) was a spillover effect of that development.
 This allow us to rule out any possible endogeneity issues that might otherwise
 arise in context such as these.
 For instance, the Afrikaans language is almost solely spoken in South Africa.
 When we observe that the introduction of the Afrikaans Google Search interface
 occurs around the same time as a growth in the number of native Afrikaans
 internet users, it will be hard to isolate the effect from the introduction
 from its cause (since an increase in native Afrikaans internet users would
 be a good reason to introduce it as an interface language).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Substantial numbers of Setswana speakers exist in Botswana, South Africa,
 Zimbabwe, and to some extend Namibia.
 However the language is most important in Botswana, where it is spoken
 by approximately 80% of all people, and where it is the only official language
 other than English.
 As such, it is also the place where most linguistic work on the Setswana
 language takes place.
 The Setswana Google Search interface was also developed at the University
 of Botswana by prof.
 Otlogetswe.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is worth noting that it is very common not to personally own a computer
 and `paying for internet access' therefore also includes a lot of people
 who use the internet in other locations such as internet cafe's.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In addition to using the propensity to spend on internet (in the last thirty
 days), we also use the propensity to own a computer as a dependent variable.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Estimation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:estimation"

\end_inset

As mentioned in the above section, we compare the change in the level of
 internet users among native Setswana speakers in South Africa, with that
 of native speakers of other language in South Africa around the introduction
 of the Setswana interface to the South-African Google Search.
 For this we use a Difference-in-Differences estimator using a native-Setswana
 speaker dummy variable (
\begin_inset Flex Code
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
setswana_logical
\end_layout

\end_inset

), interacted with a event dummy variable (
\begin_inset Flex Code
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
interface_intro
\end_layout

\end_inset

).
 The former is 
\begin_inset Flex Code
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
TRUE
\end_layout

\end_inset

 when the native language of the individual (
\begin_inset Flex Code
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
a_lng
\end_layout

\end_inset

) is 
\begin_inset Flex Code
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Setswana
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Flex Code
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
FALSE
\end_layout

\end_inset

 otherwise.
 The later is 
\begin_inset Flex Code
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
FALSE
\end_layout

\end_inset

 for data collected prior to the introduction of the Setswana interface
 language (late 2010, here wave 1 and 2) and 
\begin_inset Flex Code
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
TRUE
\end_layout

\end_inset

 after this introduction (here wave 3).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y_{irt}=\gamma_{ir}+\lambda_{it}+\delta D{}_{rt}+\zeta X_{irt}+\epsilon_{irt}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In addition to this estimation, we use an alternative specification whereby
 a factor variable of native language is interacted with the event dummy
 variable.
 In a linear regression context, factor variables are estimated as dummy
